    rdfs:comment "Aerodynamic Forces As an object moves through the atmosphere, the gas molecules of the atmosphere near the object are disturbed and move around the object." .

:Evidence_nasa_bga_spcal_structure_aware_large_s01_c00_kg00_0b47031837 a :Cl_Evidence ;
    dcterms:bibliographicCitation "page=1; section=page-1; chunk_id=nasa_bga_spcal-structure_aware_large-s01-c00" ;
    dcterms:conformsTo "confidence=0.500" ;
    dcterms:source "nasa_bga_spcal" ;
    rdfs:comment "Boundary Layer Aerodynamic forces depend in a complex way on the viscosity of the gas. As an object moves through a gas, the gas molecules stick to the surface. This creates a layer of gas near the surface, called a boundary layer, which, in effect, changes the shape of the object. The flow of gas reacts to the edge of the boundary layer as if it w" .

:Evidence_nasa_bga_spcal_structure_aware_large_s01_c00_kg01_b3ea02c23a a :Cl_Evidence ;
    dcterms:bibliographicCitation "page=1; section=page-1; chunk_id=nasa_bga_spcal-structure_aware_large-s01-c00" ;
    dcterms:conformsTo "confidence=0.500" ;
    dcterms:source "nasa_bga_spcal" ;
    rdfs:comment "The boundary layer is very important in determining the drag of an object." .

:Evidence_nasa_bga_spcal_structure_aware_large_s01_c00_kg02_c7f1d09623 a :Cl_Evidence ;
    dcterms:bibliographicCitation "page=1; section=page-1; chunk_id=nasa_bga_spcal-structure_aware_large-s01-c00" ;
    dcterms:conformsTo "confidence=0.500" ;
    dcterms:source "nasa_bga_spcal" ;
    rdfs:comment "Boundary Layer Aerodynamic forces depend in a complex way on the viscosity of the gas." .

:Evidence_nasa_bga_spcal_structure_aware_large_s01_c00_kg03_a374d5e538 a :Cl_Evidence ;
    dcterms:bibliographicCitation "page=1; section=page-1; chunk_id=nasa_bga_spcal-structure_aware_large-s01-c00" ;
    dcterms:conformsTo "confidence=0.500" ;
    dcterms:source "nasa_bga_spcal" ;
    rdfs:comment "Boundary Layer Aerodynamic forces depend in a complex way on the viscosity of the gas. As an object moves through a gas, the gas molecules stick to the surface. This creates a layer of gas near the surface, called a boundary layer, which, in effect, changes the shape of the object. The flow of gas reacts to the edge of the boundary layer as if it w" .

:Evidence_nasa_bga_spcal_structure_aware_large_s01_c00_kg04_10c627bd7d a :Cl_Evidence ;
    dcterms:bibliographicCitation "page=1; section=page-1; chunk_id=nasa_bga_spcal-structure_aware_large-s01-c00" ;
    dcterms:conformsTo "confidence=0.500" ;
    dcterms:source "nasa_bga_spcal" ;
    rdfs:comment "And to make it even more confusing, the flow conditions in and near the boundary layer are often unsteady (changing in time)." .

:Evidence_nasa_bga_spcal_structure_aware_large_s02_c00_kg00_3fbc6a6782 a :Cl_Evidence ;
    dcterms:bibliographicCitation "page=2; section=page-2; chunk_id=nasa_bga_spcal-structure_aware_large-s02-c00" ;
    dcterms:conformsTo "confidence=0.500" ;
    dcterms:source "nasa_bga_spcal" ;
    rdfs:comment "From a detailed analysis of the momentum conservation equation , the inertial forces are characterized by the product of the density r times the velocity V times the gradient of the velocity dV/dx ." .

:Evidence_nasa_bga_spcal_structure_aware_large_s02_c00_kg01_a374d5e538 a :Cl_Evidence ;
    dcterms:bibliographicCitation "page=2; section=page-2; chunk_id=nasa_bga_spcal-structure_aware_large-s02-c00" ;
    dcterms:conformsTo "confidence=0.500" ;
    dcterms:source "nasa_bga_spcal" ;
    rdfs:comment "High values of the parameter (on the order of 10 million) indicate that viscous forces are small, and the flow is essentially inviscid." .

:Evidence_nasa_bga_spcal_structure_aware_large_s02_c01_kg00_b609fa2d1f a :Cl_Evidence ;
    dcterms:bibliographicCitation "page=2; section=page-2; chunk_id=nasa_bga_spcal-structure_aware_large-s02-c01" ;
    dcterms:conformsTo "confidence=0.500" ;
    dcterms:source "nasa_bga_spcal" ;
    rdfs:comment "The Reynolds number can be further simplified if we use the kinematic viscosity nu that is equal to the dynamic viscosity divided by the density: \\(\\LARGE \\nu = \\frac{\\mu}{\\rho} \\) \\(\\LARGE \\text{Re} = \\frac{V \\, L}{\\nu} \\) For some problems, we can divide the Reynolds by the length scale to obtain the Reynolds number per foot Ref . This is given b" .

